{{Infobox stadium | stadium_name = Het Houten Stadion | location = [[Amsterdam]] | coordinates = | opened = July 9, 1907 | closed = December 8, 1934 | demolished = 1935 | surface = Grass | owner = [[AFC Ajax]] | architect = [[Jordanus Roodenburgh|Daan Roodenburgh]] | tenants = [[AFC Ajax]] ([[Netherlands Football League Championship]]) (1907-1934) | seating_capacity = 15,000 }} '''Het Houten Stadion''' ([[English language|English]]: ''The Wooden Stadium'') is a former stadium of [[AFC Ajax]] which served as the team's home stadium from 1907 to 1934.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.geheugenvanoost.nl/22708/nl/het-houten-ajax-stadion-1911-1934 |title=Het Houten Ajax-Stadion (1911-1934) |publisher=Geheugen van Oost|accessdate=2013-08-30}}</ref>
==History== Het Houten Stadion is a former stadium of AFC Ajax. Before Ajax moved to this stadium, they had played on a field in [[Amsterdam-Noord]]. Houses had been built on their field in 1907 which sent Ajax searching for a new place to play.
The club found two locations in the [[municipality]] of [[Watergraafsmeer]] losing their previous pitch to housing development. Both new places were located on the [[Polder]], but were closer than the former field in Noord.
In the early years of the grounds there was no actual stadium, there were no stands, no water and the players would change and get ready in a bar nearby. The first stands were built in 1911 with covered seating on one side, and standing tribunes on the other. In 1916 the stands were built behind both goal lines. Designed by architect and Ajax-member [[Jordanus Roodenburgh|Daan Roodenburgh]], the funding for the stadium came from Wim Eggerman, a local businessman, who was the president of the club at the time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.metronieuws.nl/regionaal/5-historische-ajax-plekken/SrZljo!MOHCqK7yI0pkQ/ |title=5 historische Ajax-plekken |publisher=Metro Nieuws|accessdate=2013-08-30}}</ref>
With the success of [[AFC Ajax]] in the 1930s the stadium became too small. Every match more people would come to see Ajax play, the last [[Klassieker]] match to be played at Het Houten Stadion against [[Feyenoord]] was so busy, no corners could be taken during that match because there were spectators spilling out on to the pitch. 15,000 spectators attended that match. On 9 December 1934, Ajax moved to their new [[De Meer Stadion]].
In 1936 Daan Roodenburgh competed in the [[Art competitions at the 1936 Summer Olympics]] in [[Berlin]] in the Mixed Architecture event for Sports venues with his construction of Het Houten Stadion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ro/daan-roodenburgh-1.html |title=Daan Roodenburgh / Olympic Sports |publisher=Sports-reference.com |accessdate=2013-11-20 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131204005811/http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ro/daan-roodenburgh-1.html |archivedate=2013-12-04 |df= }}</ref>
There is now an [[Albert Heijn]] situated in the location of the former main entrance to the stadium on Middenweg in the Watergraafsmeer.
